'''Velenje''' ({{lang-de|W<U+00F6>llan}}) is a municipality with 33.331 inhabitants in the northeast of [[Slovenia]]. Stari Velenje (the old part at the foot of the castle) is mentioned for the first time 1264 and 1374 as small market town and was a center of handicraft and trade. Due to [[lignite]] mining, the city expanded especially after [[World War II]]. After the death of [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|Yugoslav]] president for life [[Josip Broz Tito|Tito]] it was renamed [[List of places named after Tito|Titovo Velenje]] in 1981, but the old name was returned to the city in 1991, shortly before Slovenia became independent.

Velenje is the headquarters of [[Gorenje]], a manufacturer of [[major appliance|household appliances]], and the former hometown of [[Jolanda <U+010C>eplak]], a Slovenian [[middle distance track event|middle distance]] [[Athletics (track and field)|athlete]] and Olympic bronze medalist. It is also the hometown of [[Katarina Srebotnik]], a Slovenian [[tennis player]].

